            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is the critical angle?</h2>
              <p>
                When light passes from one transparent medium to another (for
                example, from glass to air), it bends according to Snell’s law.
                If the light travels from a
                <strong>denser medium</strong> (higher refractive index) to a
                <strong>less dense medium</strong> (lower refractive index),
                there is a special incident angle called the
                <strong>critical angle</strong>.
              </p>
              <p>
                The <strong>critical angle</strong> is the angle of incidence in
                the denser medium for which the angle of refraction in the less
                dense medium is exactly <strong>90°</strong>. For any larger
                incident angle, the refracted ray disappears and all the light
                is reflected back into the denser medium. This phenomenon is
                called <strong>total internal reflection (TIR)</strong>.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Snell’s law</p>
                <p>\( n_1 \sin\theta_1 = n_2 \sin\theta_2 \)</p>
                <p class="mt-2 font-semibold mb-1">Critical angle condition</p>
                <p>
                  At the critical angle, the refracted angle is \( \theta_2 =
                  90^\circ \), so \( \sin\theta_2 = 1 \).
                </p>
                <p class="mt-1">
                  \( n_1 \sin\theta_c = n_2 \cdot 1 \Rightarrow \sin\theta_c =
                  \dfrac{n_2}{n_1} \)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-1 font-semibold">
                  \( \theta_c = \arcsin\left(\dfrac{n_2}{n_1}\right) \) &nbsp;
                  (only if \( n_1 &gt; n_2 \))
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Conditions for total internal reflection</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong
                    >Light must travel from a higher-index medium to a
                    lower-index medium</strong
                  >, i.e. \( n_1 &gt; n_2 \). For example, glass → air or water
                  → air.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong
                    >The incident angle must be greater than the critical
                    angle</strong
                  >, \( \theta_i &gt; \theta_c \).
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                If either condition is not satisfied, total internal reflection
                cannot occur. The calculator checks these conditions and tells
                you whether a critical angle exists for your chosen media.
              </p>

              <h2>Worked examples</h2>

              <h3>Example 1 – Glass to air</h3>
              <p>
                Suppose light travels from crown glass (\( n_1 \approx 1.50 \))
                into air (\( n_2 \approx 1.00 \)).
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \( \sin\theta_c = \dfrac{n_2}{n_1} = \dfrac{1.00}{1.50} =
                  0.666\ldots \)
                </p>
                <p>\( \theta_c = \arcsin(0.666\ldots) \approx 41.8^\circ \)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Any incident angle in the glass greater than about
                <strong>41.8°</strong> will produce total internal reflection at
                the glass–air boundary. This is the principle behind
                <strong>optical fibers</strong> and many imaging systems.
              </p>

              <h3>Example 2 – Water to air</h3>
              <p>
                For light going from water (\( n_1 \approx 1.33 \)) to air (\(
                n_2 \approx 1.00 \)):
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\( \sin\theta_c = \dfrac{1.00}{1.33} \approx 0.7519 \)</p>
                <p>\( \theta_c = \arcsin(0.7519) \approx 48.8^\circ \)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                This explains the shimmering “mirror” you see when you look up
                from underwater at shallow angles: rays with incident angle
                greater than about <strong>48.8°</strong> are totally internally
                reflected.
              </p>

              <h3>Example 3 – Air to glass (no critical angle)</h3>
              <p>
                Now reverse the direction: light travels from air (\( n_1
                \approx 1.00 \)) into glass (\( n_2 \approx 1.50 \)).
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \( \sin\theta_c = \dfrac{n_2}{n_1} = \dfrac{1.50}{1.00} = 1.50
                  \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  But \( \sin\theta \) cannot be greater than 1, so
                  <strong>no real critical angle exists</strong>.
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                In this case, light always has a refracted component in the
                glass, regardless of the incident angle. Total internal
                reflection is impossible when light goes from a lower-index
                medium to a higher-index medium.
              </p>

              <h2>Common refractive indices (approximate)</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>Vacuum: \( n = 1.0000 \)</li>
                <li>Air (STP): \( n \approx 1.0003 \)</li>
                <li>Water (visible light): \( n \approx 1.33 \)</li>
                <li>Acrylic (PMMA): \( n \approx 1.49 \)</li>
                <li>Crown glass: \( n \approx 1.50 \)</li>
                <li>
                  Immersion oil (microscopy): \( n \approx 1.515\text{–}1.52 \)
                </li>
                <li>Diamond: \( n \approx 2.42 \)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Real refractive indices depend on <strong>wavelength</strong>,
                <strong>temperature</strong>, and material composition. For most
                classroom and exam problems, the approximate values above are
                sufficient.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>What is the physical meaning of the critical angle?</h3>
              <p>
                At the critical angle, the refracted ray just
                <strong>grazes along the interface</strong> between the two
                media. Beyond this angle, Snell’s law predicts a refracted angle
                greater than 90°, which is not physically possible, so the wave
                is instead completely reflected back into the denser medium.
              </p>

              <h3>Why is total internal reflection important?</h3>
              <p>
                Total internal reflection allows light to be guided with very
                low loss. It is the key principle behind:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Optical fibers</strong> for internet and
                  telecommunications
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Endoscopes</strong> and other medical imaging devices
                </li>
                <li><strong>Prisms</strong> in binoculars and cameras</li>
                <li>
                  Some <strong>mirage</strong> and atmospheric optical effects
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Does wavelength (color) affect the critical angle?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. The refractive index \( n \) is slightly different for
                different wavelengths (dispersion). Blue light usually has a
                higher refractive index than red light in the same material, so
                its critical angle is slightly smaller. The calculator assumes a
                single effective refractive index; for precise work you would
                use wavelength-specific values.
              </p>

              <h3>How is this tested on exams like the MCAT or A‑level?</h3>
              <p>Typical questions ask you to:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Compute the critical angle for a given pair of media</li>
                <li>
                  Decide whether a given incident angle leads to refraction or
                  total internal reflection
                </li>
                <li>
                  Apply Snell’s law qualitatively (which way does the ray bend?)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator above mirrors this workflow: pick \( n_1 \) and
                \( n_2 \), get \( \theta_c \), and test any incident angle to
                see the behavior.
              </p>
            </section>
